Prologue
“I beg you!” Queen Eirwen pleaded, “don’t send her away! She is still a child!” The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought, his gaze darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue strands. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, he had only fathered sons up to this point.
“You have two options: either you kill the child or you send her into the wilderness. This is her punishment for your failure, Eirwen.” He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while in the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and a never-ending war broke out between the two kingdoms, until finally the South offered a truce.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
“I beg you, my king, do with me what you will, lock me up, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child,” pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with utter contempt. Perhaps, but only perhaps, would he show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and who had given him his sons.
“Well, the child can stay in the palace,” he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen stared at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. “Yes, my king.” She bowed her head.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's private rooms. Then he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution square, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution square, a loud uproar erupted among the citizens when they realized that their only, beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Again others questioned why this should happen, but all were in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman, who had just been a queen, was to be burned. No one had deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the most terrible thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king delivered a speech declaring how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and did not accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the farthest room in the southern wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by wondered what was inside the room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors among the maids circulated. It was said that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and was waiting to be let out.
Her assumption could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory, and she headed toward the southern wing, while the servants walked around and whispered to each other. They had no idea what was hidden behind the door.
The rumors naturally also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" Ivory whispered before the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered whether – unlike the last time – entry would actually be granted. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from inside, probably to indicate that she was there. Where else would she be?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory. Previously, Ivory had entered without asking.
Around the corner, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "Yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound coming from what was supposedly an empty room, although Ivory had been entering there for several years.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little or no light. In addition, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a blizzard had swept through.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is this?" asked Ivory and sat next to Kari on the bed.
